    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Don't worry too much about the dripping water; a little seepage while you work is often just a sign that the old washer is still holding a tiny bit of pressure, so grab your rag and be ready for a small splash. As for the pipes, you generally won't damage them unless you use excessive force, but you should take your time and use the adjustable wrench gently if you need to loosen the connection to the stem. One key thing to watch out for is your own hands, since working in a dim bathroom with wet tools can be slippery, so make sure your hands are dry when holding the wrench to prevent slipping and scratching the porcelain. If you feel resistance when pulling the stem, stop immediately and check if a plastic retaining clip or a small screw is holding it in place rather than forcing it out, which could crack the stem. If you need to replace the washer, double-check that the new one is the exact same size and shape, or you might end up with a leak again later.",
      "source": "target",
